bout 1287":"about 1287","Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England":"Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England","Chute, Wiltshire, England":"Chute, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cordray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>coer de roi</i> ‘(having the) heart of a king’. This surname is now extinct in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Cordry","meanings":["English: variant of   Cordray  ."]},{"name":"Cordrey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Cordray  . Alternatively, possibly derived from Old French <i>corderie</i> ‘ropery, rope-walk’, taken to mean a worker at a ropery."]},{"name":"Cordery","meanings":["English: variant of   Cordray  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":14,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":45,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Cordray I was born about 1245, in Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England as the son of Roger Cordery II and Clitheroe. He had at least 1 son with Warham. He died about 1290, at the age of 47."},"et":{"about 1245–about 1290":"umbes 1245–umbes 1290","1245–1290":"1245–1290","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","1287–1309":"1287–1309","1210–1249":"1210–1249","–1250":"–1250","about 1250":"umbes 1250","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1249":"1249","about 1219":"umbes 1219","1259":"1259","1245":"1245","1255":"1255","1210":"1210","1287":"1287","about 1245":"umbes 1245","1309":"1309","about 1287":"umbes 1287","Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England":"Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England","Chute, Wiltshire, England":"Chute, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1245–about 1290":"noin 1245–noin 1290","1245–1290":"1245–1290","1255–Female":"1255–Kuollut","1287–1309":"1287–1309","1210–1249":"1210–1249","–1250":"–1250","about 1250":"noin 1250","about 1290":"noin 1290","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1249":"1249","about 1219":"noin 1